Place the following key files here before starting debproxy:

  debian-archive-keyring.asc
      Debian archive signing key.
      Source: /usr/share/keyrings/debian-archive-keyring.gpg on any Debian system,
      or: https://ftp-master.debian.org/keys/

      Export in armored form:
        gpg --dearmor < /usr/share/keyrings/debian-archive-keyring.gpg \
          | gpg --armor > debian-archive-keyring.asc

  ubuntu-archive-keyring.asc
      Ubuntu archive signing key.
      Source: /usr/share/keyrings/ubuntu-archive-keyring.gpg on any Ubuntu system.

      Export in armored form:
        gpg --dearmor < /usr/share/keyrings/ubuntu-archive-keyring.gpg \
          | gpg --armor > ubuntu-archive-keyring.asc

  debproxy-signing.asc
      Debproxy's own repository signing key (private key, armored).
      Generate a new key:
        gpg --batch --gen-key <<EOF
        %no-protection
        Key-Type: EdDSA
        Key-Curve: Ed25519
        Name-Real: debproxy
        Name-Email: debproxy@example.com
        Expire-Date: 0
        EOF
        gpg --armor --export-secret-keys debproxy@example.com > debproxy-signing.asc

      After starting the container, publish the public key to the store once:
        docker compose run --rm publish-key

      Clients add the public key with:
        curl http://<debproxy-host>:8080/keys/debproxy.asc \
          | sudo tee /usr/share/keyrings/debproxy.asc

      And use a sources.list entry such as:
        deb [signed-by=/usr/share/keyrings/debproxy.asc] \
          http://<debproxy-host>:8080/current/debian trixie main
